PRosettaC — Docker edition
==========================

This fork of PRosettaC adds a containerized setup so the pipeline runs on any
machine with Docker, without manually installing Rosetta, PatchDock, or an HPC
scheduler. The original HPC install (PBS/SGE/SLURM) still works; see the
"Native install" section at the bottom.


What this fork changes
----------------------

- Dockerfile + docker-compose.yml for a one-command build.
- cluster/Local — new scheduler backend that runs batches inline on one box,
  so the container doesn't need PBS/SGE/SLURM.
- docker/fetch-patchdock.sh — runtime downloader that prompts for the
  PatchDock license info (name/affiliation/email) and installs PatchDock on
  first run. Cached via a bind-mounted volume.
- Rosetta binary + database pulled from the official rosettacommons/rosetta
  Docker image; the Python helper scripts (molfile_to_params.py, clean_pdb.py)
  sparse-checked-out from the public RosettaCommons repos at pinned commit
  SHAs.
- Env var read as ROSETTA3_HOME (with ROSETTA_FOL fallback) so the image
  works under Apple Rosetta 2 on Apple Silicon, which rejects any process
  that sets an unknown ROSETTA_* env var.


Quick start
-----------

    docker build -t prosettac .

    mkdir -p patchdock_cache work
    cp YourProtac_params.txt YourInputs.* work/

    # Interactive — prompts for PatchDock license on first run:
    docker run --rm -it \
      -v "$PWD/patchdock_cache:/opt/patchdock" \
      -v "$PWD/work:/work" \
      prosettac auto.py YourProtac_params.txt

    # Non-interactive (CI/batch):
    docker run --rm \
      -e PATCHDOCK_FULLNAME="Jane Doe" \
      -e PATCHDOCK_AFFILIATION="Example University" \
      -e PATCHDOCK_EMAIL="jane@example.edu" \
      -v "$PWD/patchdock_cache:/opt/patchdock" \
      -v "$PWD/work:/work" \
      prosettac auto.py YourProtac_params.txt

Results land in work/Results/ on the host.

Or via compose:

    ROSETTA_IMAGE=rosettacommons/rosetta:serial \
    PATCHDOCK_CACHE=./patchdock_cache \
    PROSETTAC_WORK=./work \
    docker compose run --rm prosettac auto.py YourProtac_params.txt


How the image is assembled
--------------------------

The Dockerfile is multi-stage:

  rosettacommons/rosetta:serial  ->  stage "rosetta"
     |
     |   compiled binary + libs from /usr/local/bin
     |   Rosetta database from .../pyrosetta/database
     v
  continuumio/miniconda3 (Debian trixie, linux/amd64) -> final stage
     + apt: build-essential, git, curl, file, unzip, tcsh, libgl1, ...
     + conda env "prosettac" (python 3.11, rdkit, numpy, scikit-learn,
                              openbabel, pymol-open-source)
     + conda env "py27" (python 2.7 for Rosetta's molfile_to_params.py)
     + git sparse-checkout of RosettaCommons/rosetta and RosettaCommons/tools
       at pinned commit SHAs (SCRIPTS_REPO_SHA, TOOLS_REPO_SHA)
     + COPY of Rosetta binaries + database from the "rosetta" stage into
       /opt/rosetta/main/... (matches paths PRosettaC hardcodes)
     + COPY of this repo into /opt/prosettac

Runtime layout inside the container:

    /opt/rosetta/main/source/bin/rosetta_scripts.default.linuxgccrelease
    /opt/rosetta/main/source/scripts/python/public/molfile_to_params.py
    /opt/rosetta/main/database/               (ROSETTA3_DB points here)
    /opt/rosetta/tools/protein_tools/scripts/clean_pdb.py
    /opt/patchdock/                           (populated on first run)
    /opt/prosettac/                           (this repo)
    /work                                     (bind mount — your inputs/outputs)

The image is ~3 GB. Most of that is the Rosetta database.


Configuration
-------------

Params file format (auto.py / short.py):

    PDB: PDB_ID1 PDB_ID2          # or explicit .pdb files — see below
    LIG: LIG_ID1 LIG_ID2          # or explicit .sdf files
    PROTAC: protac.smi
    Full: True
    ClusterName: Local            # recommended inside Docker

Instead of PDB/LIG IDs, explicit files are allowed with the [ID ; file]
syntax — e.g. `PDB: [6BOY ; my_struct.pdb] [5T35 ; other.pdb]`.

For the manual entry points (main.py / extended.py):

    Structures: StructA.pdb StructB.pdb
    Chains: A B
    Heads: HeadA.sdf HeadB.sdf
    Anchor atoms: 11 23
    Protac: protac.smi
    Full: True
    ClusterName: Local

Notes:
- Full: False runs a shorter, lower-quality sampling.
- The params file must not be called params.txt (reserved name).
- Protac is a .smi file with the full PROTAC SMILES on a single line.
- Anchor atoms are 1-indexed; the anchor must be uniquely defined in the
  PROTAC SMILES.

Scheduler options:
- ClusterName: Local   — runs each batch inline (default for Docker).
- ClusterName: PBS     — PBS (default if omitted; assumes qsub/qstat).
- ClusterName: SGE     — Sun Grid Engine / OGS.
- ClusterName: SLURM   — Slurm Workload Manager.

For non-Local schedulers, see cluster/Cluster.py for the interface. Set
SCHEDULER_PARAMS to a file whose contents are prepended to each job file —
useful for CPU counts, conda activation lines, etc.

Memory knobs (both in MB, per job):
- RosettaDockMemory  (default 8000) — local docking step.
- ProtacModelMemory  (default 4000) — linker conformer generation.


Entry points
------------

  auto.py       Full automatic pipeline: fetch PDB, prepare ligands, dock,
                generate PROTAC conformers, cluster results.
  main.py       Manual pipeline: you supply the prepared structures, binder
                .sdf files, chain IDs, and anchor-atom indices.
  short.py      auto.py wrapper that submits the whole run as a single job.
  extended.py   main.py wrapper that submits the whole run as a single job.


Inputs
------

Input files for auto.py go in your /work bind mount. The `PDB:` line can
reference a remote PDB ID (fetched via PyMOL) or a local .pdb file. The
`LIG:` line can reference a PDB ligand three-letter code, or a local .sdf
file. Ligand SDFs must be positioned in their binding pose within the
corresponding receptor.


Native install (HPC / no Docker)
--------------------------------

If you cannot use Docker, the original flow still works:

1. Load Python 3 (the original study used 3.6.4).
2. Install RDKit, NumPy, PyMOL, scikit-learn, OpenBabel.
3. Install Rosetta (https://www.rosettacommons.org/) and PatchDock
   (https://bio3d.cs.huji.ac.il/webserver/patchdock/).
4. Set env vars:
     export PATCHDOCK=/path/to/patchdock
     export OB=/path/to/openbabel
     export SCRIPTS_FOL=/path/to/this/repo/
     export ROSETTA_FOL=/path/to/rosetta     # or ROSETTA3_HOME
5. Set scheduler paths as appropriate (PBS_HOME, SGE_HOME, or Slurm) and
   set PBS_O_WORKDIR / equivalent for each job.

Then:   python auto.py YourProtac_params.txt


